Fig. 2
 shows the XRD patterns of catalysts and their components. The pattern of TNTA obtained after calcination at 450 °C exhibited peaks at 25.4°, 37.9°, 48.1°, 54.1°, 55.1°, 62.7°, 68.9°, 70.3°, and 75.0° corresponding to planes of anatase TiO2 (PDF#21-1272), respectively (

). A characteristic peak of Ti at 40° was also observed (▼), as the TNTA layer on the base Ti sheet was very thin. No characteristic peak of rutile TiO2 at 27.8° was observed, i.e., the above phase did not form.

The photocatalyst phase composition was further probed by Raman spectroscopy (Fig. 3
                        ). All samples showed obvious anatase peaks at 395 (B1g), 514 (A1g + B1g), and 636 (Eg) cm−1, whereas no rutile TiO2 peaks were observed (

                        ). Thus, both XRD patterns and Raman spectra indicated that TNTA obtained after calcination at 450 °C contained anatase as the only phase. Moreover, CDs/TNTA and Ag/CDs/TNTA showed peaks at 1361.6 and 1575.6 cm−1, respectively (▼). These signals corresponded to the G- and D-bands of CDs, indicating that CDs were present in both CDs/TNTA and Ag/CDs/TNTAs. The intensity ratio (I
                        D/I
                        G) of these peaks equaled 0.982, 0.898, 0.893, and 0.898 for CDs/TNTA, 1-Ag/CDs/TNTA, 2-Ag/CDs/TNTA, and 3-Ag/CDs/TNTA, respectively. The decrease in this ratio observed after Ag NP introduction indicated that CD amorphousness was concomitantly enhanced. Besides, the characteristic peak of TiO2 gained intensity after the loading of Ag NPs because of their promotional effect on Raman scattering.
